    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9992a613_9d7760cf",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/database/database.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 35,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003211
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-11-08T01:48:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "You were storing the db pointer as a context value [1], but I don\u0027t believe this is correct. According to the context docs, context values should be request-scoped [2], while the sql docs say that the open connection should be called once and shared globally [3]. Therefore I believe that singleton is the right approach, that way every concurrent request in the same instance of the app will share the same database connection.\n\n[1] https://chrome-internal.googlesource.com/infra/infra_internal/+/4e3f4742a24613c69ddb92d0facfdde5c7294836/go/src/infra_internal/crimson/server/crimsondb/crimsondb.go#737\n[2] https://golang.org/pkg/context/\n[3] https://golang.org/pkg/database/sql/#Open",
      "revId": "f6c8f6a7d0aadbc712cdbecbfb3a91aedc0fc2f7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ab4da072_a73c4fd0",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/database/database.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 35,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002539
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-11-08T23:11:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The database handle was stored as a global variable (see https://chrome-internal.googlesource.com/infra/infra_internal/+/4e3f4742a24613c69ddb92d0facfdde5c7294836/go/src/infra_internal/crimson/server/crimsondb/crimsondb.go#734) and was shared between requests. It was put into the context just for easier mocking in tests.\n\nThe problem with global variables is that they are shared by everything. In particular, using global variables complicates tests, because tests now share state (and can\u0027t run in parallel anymore if this state is mocked). \n\nOne solution to this is to make functions/methods accept implementations (real ones or mocks) via arguments, e.g. imaging you want to mock the database in EnsureDatacenters:\n  \n  func EnsureDatacenters(c context.Context, datacenters []*config.DatacenterConfig, db DBInterface) error {\n    ...\n  }\n\nThen the prod code would be:\n\n db, _ :\u003d getDatabaseConnection(c)\n EnsureDatacenters(c, datacenters, db) \n\nAnd testing code would be:\n\n db :\u003d NewMockedDB()\n EnsureDatacenters(c, datacenters, db) \n\nThis is fine, but becomes cumbersome very fast, since in most cases this \u0027db\u0027 (or similar variables) must be passed down the stack to other functions.\n\nThis is where context comes in. It incapsulates all such sort-of-global-but-not-really variables. Since we always pass context down the stack, all functions get access to the stuff inside the context.\n\nSo the prod code becomes:\n\n  db, _ :\u003d getDatabaseConnection(c)\n  ctx :\u003d WithDatabase(ctx, db)\n  EnsureDatacenters(c, datacenters)\n\nAnd testing code correspondingly becomes:\n\n  db :\u003d NewMockedDB(c)\n  ctx :\u003d WithDatabase(ctx, db)\n  EnsureDatacenters(c, datacenters)\n\nYou\u0027ll see this pattern very often in luci-go codebase. (It is sometimes over-abused...).",
      "parentUuid": "9992a613_9d7760cf",
      "revId": "f6c8f6a7d0aadbc712cdbecbfb3a91aedc0fc2f7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f2f07f70_ccc0d73d",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/database/database.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 35,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003211
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-11-09T02:55:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Got it, but I\u0027m not sure where the best place in the context-passing chain is to install the database. For example, currently importConfigs calls EnsureDatacenters, and EnsureDatacenters needs the db directly (it doesn\u0027t call anything else that needs the db). I see three options:\n1. EnsureDatacenters is the first thing that needs the db, so it calls getDatabaseConnection itself. It doesn\u0027t install it in the context because nothing else needs it.\n2. importConfigs \"knows\" (should it know?) that EnsureDatacenters will need the db, so it calls getDatabaseConnection and installs it in the context before calling EnsureDatacenters.\n3. Some middleware knows that eventually the db will be needed by this HTTP handler, so it calls getDatabaseConnection and installs it in the context for importConfigs. importConfigs doesn\u0027t know or care about this value, but when it calls EnsureDatacenters, EnsureDatacenters expects and uses it.\n\nI think #1 or #3 is best because it should either be as close to where it\u0027s needed as possible or just generally installed for most (all?) HTTP handlers. #2 doesn\u0027t seem right because it means importConfigs has too much knowledge of what EnsureDatacenters is actually doing to ensure datacenters.\n\nFor now I\u0027ve done #3 but let me know if you think some other option is better.",
      "parentUuid": "ab4da072_a73c4fd0",
      "revId": "f6c8f6a7d0aadbc712cdbecbfb3a91aedc0fc2f7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5469a769_4a5932d0",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/database/database.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 35,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002539
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-11-15T01:03:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "We generally use approach #3 in similar situations. DB is \"global\" service in this app, so it makes sense to install it globally in a root middleware.",
      "parentUuid": "f2f07f70_ccc0d73d",
      "revId": "f6c8f6a7d0aadbc712cdbecbfb3a91aedc0fc2f7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4c6aa474_1891fda4",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/database/database.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 62,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002539
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-11-08T23:11:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "this looks very weird :)\n\nAs I said below, there\u0027s no need to use RLock around db at outer functions. \n\nThe logic of this function should be similar to:\n\n  connectionString :\u003d \u003cfetched from settings\u003e\n  \n  // Optimistic path: already have the DB cached.\n  dbLock.RLock()\n  curDB, curConStr :\u003d db, dbConnectionString\n  dbLock.RUnlock()\n  if curConStr \u003d\u003d connectionString {\n    return curDB\n  }\n\n  // Pessimistic path.\n  dbLock.Lock()\n  defer dbLock.Unlock()\n  \n  if dbConnectionString \u003d\u003d connectionString {\n    return db // someone else initialized it already\n  }\n \n  dbConnectionString \u003d connectionString\n  db \u003d \u003cinitialize\u003e\n\n  return db",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 61,
        "startChar": 2,
        "endLine": 62,
        "endChar": 15
      },
      "revId": "f6c8f6a7d0aadbc712cdbecbfb3a91aedc0fc2f7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e5be5ebd_5b8f9a71",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/database/database.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 62,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003211
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-11-09T02:55:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I assumed that since we\u0027re returning a pointer here, we want to avoid changing the underlying value at the memory address the pointer refers to for as long as anyone has access to the pointer, in case they dereference it and suddenly it refers to some other database connection.\n\nIn other words if we return db and db is a *sql.DB, I don\u0027t want some other concurrent request to do *db \u003d sql.Open(...). I see now that I am not setting *db, I\u0027m setting db, so the pointer itself is changing when there\u0027s a new connection string.\n\nAnyways, this is done.",
      "parentUuid": "4c6aa474_1891fda4",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 61,
        "startChar": 2,
        "endLine": 62,
        "endChar": 15
      },
      "revId": "f6c8f6a7d0aadbc712cdbecbfb3a91aedc0fc2f7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4fbe7dc3_55a4b801",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/database/database.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 62,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002539
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-11-15T01:03:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "In go there\u0027s expectation that programmers follow \"pass by value\" and \"pass by pointer\" conventions. Beefy stateful objects (like *sql.DB) are usually passed by pointer everywhere, and it is expected that people do not generally do *db \u003d sql.DB{}.\n\nGenerally if there are some hidden fields in the object (see \"// contains filtered or unexported fields\" in https://golang.org/pkg/database/sql/#DB), then the object is most likely expected to be passed by pointer everywhere.\n\nPass by value is usually used only for small structs that just carry some data.",
      "parentUuid": "e5be5ebd_5b8f9a71",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 61,
        "startChar": 2,
        "endLine": 62,
        "endChar": 15
      },
      "revId": "f6c8f6a7d0aadbc712cdbecbfb3a91aedc0fc2f7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "800516f7_ab71e467",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/database/database.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
